      <hedline>
        <hl1>Beyond Our Shores</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marcia P Neeley letter says too many Americans cannot see beyond their immediate world, and few recognize existence of interdependent global village (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''A Whole New World'' (column, Aug. 8), Thomas L. Friedman suggests that George W. Bush and his father's foreign policy advisers do not understand today's new global system. While that is true, the presidential election will not be won or lost over foreign policy concerns.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''A Whole New World'' (column, Aug. 8), Thomas L. Friedman suggests that George W. Bush and his father's foreign policy advisers do not understand today's new global system. While that is true, the presidential election will not be won or lost over foreign policy concerns.</p>
        <p>Millions of Americans can't seem to see beyond their computers and cell phones. The ''whole new world,'' for most people, translates into their town, city and state, not the world beyond. Few see an interdependent global village, and the value of engaging in and caring for a larger society on which the lives of our children and grandchildren will depend.</p>
        <p>MARCIA P. NEELEY  New York, Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
